# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: marimekko-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] In statistics, a **contingency table** (also known as a **cross tabulation** or **crosstab**) is a type of table in a matrix format that displays the multivariate frequency distribution of the variables.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] They are heavily used in survey research, business intelligence, engineering, and scientific research.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] They provide a basic picture of the interrelation between two variables and can help find interactions between them.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The term *contingency table* was first used by Karl Pearson in "On the Theory of Contingency and Its Relation to Association and Normal Correlation", part of the *Drapers' Company Research Memoirs Biometric Series I* published in 1904.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] A crucial problem of multivariate statistics is finding the (direct-)dependence structure underlying the variables contained in high-dimensional contingency tables.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] If some of the conditional independences are revealed, then even the storage of the data can be done in a smarter way (see Lauritzen (2002)).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] In order to do this one can use information theory concepts, which gain the information only from the distribution of probability, which can be expressed easily from the contingency table by the relative frequencies.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] A pivot table is a way to create contingency tables using spreadsheet software.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Suppose there are two variables, sex (male or female) and handedness (right- or left-handed).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Further suppose that 100 individuals are randomly sampled from a very large population as part of a study of sex differences in handedness.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] A contingency table can be created to display the numbers of individuals who are male right-handed and left-handed, female right-handed and left-handed.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Such a contingency table is shown below.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The numbers of the males, females, and right- and left-handed individuals are called marginal totals.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The grand total (the total number of individuals represented in the contingency table) is the number in the bottom right corner.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The table allows users to see at a glance that the proportion of men who are right-handed is about the same as the proportion of women who are right-handed although the proportions are not identical.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The strength of the association can be measured by the odds ratio, and the population odds ratio estimated by the sample odds ratio.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] If the proportions of individuals in the different columns vary significantly between rows (or vice versa), it is said that there is a *contingency* between the two variables.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] In other words, the two variables are *not* independent.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] If there is no contingency, it is said that the two variables are *independent*.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The example above is the simplest kind of contingency table, a table in which each variable has only two levels; this is called a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] In principle, any number of rows and columns may be used.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] There may also be more than two variables, but higher order contingency tables are difficult to represent visually.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The relation between ordinal variables, or between ordinal and categorical variables, may also be represented in contingency tables, although such a practice is rare.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] For more on the use of a contingency table for the relation between two ordinal variables, see Goodman and Kruskal's gamma.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The degree of association between the two variables can be assessed by a number of coefficients.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The following subsections describe a few of them.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] For a more complete discussion of their uses, see the main articles linked under each subsection heading.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The simplest measure of association for a 2 × 2 contingency table is the odds ratio.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Given two events, A and B, the odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of A in the presence of B and the odds of A in the absence of B, or equivalently (due to symmetry), the ratio of the odds of B in the presence of A and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio is 1; if the odds ratio is greater than 1, the events are positively associated; if the odds ratio is less than 1, the events are negatively associated.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Then its sign equals the sign of the product of the main diagonal elements of the table minus the product of the off–diagonal elements. φ takes on the minimum value −1.0 or the maximum value of +1.0 if and only if every marginal proportion is equal to 0.5 (and two diagonal cells are empty).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Two alternatives are the *contingency coefficient* *C*, and Cramér's V.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Another choice is the tetrachoric correlation coefficient but it is only applicable to 2 × 2 tables.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Polychoric correlation is an extension of the tetrachoric correlation to tables involving variables with more than two levels.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Tetrachoric correlation assumes that the variable underlying each dichotomous measure is normally distributed.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The tetrachoric correlation coefficient should not be confused with the Pearson correlation coefficient computed by assigning, say, values 0.0 and 1.0 to represent the two levels of each variable (which is mathematically equivalent to the φ coefficient).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The lambda coefficient is a measure of the strength of association of the cross tabulations when the variables are measured at the nominal level.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Values range from 0.0 (no association) to 1.0 (the maximum possible association).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Asymmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement in predicting the dependent variable.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Symmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement when prediction is done in both directions.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] The uncertainty coefficient, or Theil's U, is another measure for variables at the nominal level.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Its values range from −1.0 (100% negative association, or perfect inversion) to +1.0 (100% positive association, or perfect agreement).
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] A value of 0.0 indicates the absence of association.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] This asymmetrical property can lead to insights not as evident in symmetrical measures of association.
[src:marimekko-charts/contingency-table] Gamma, Tau-b and Tau-c are used when the categories or levels of both variables have a natural order.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Two designers in particular, Vuokko Nurmesniemi, with bold stripes, and Maija Isola, with large simple flowered prints such as the ***Unikko*** poppy, created hundreds of distinctive patterns and helped to make Marimekko a household name across the world.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The co-founder, Armi Ratia, first considered *Armi* as the company's name, but it was already registered.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Her middle name was Maria, shortened to *Mari*; her husband Viljo thought of different names for women's clothing.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In her home town of Koivisto, Armi heard people talking about dresses (Finnish: *mekko*), and so she came to the name Marimekko.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Marimekko was founded in 1951 by Viljo and Armi Ratia, after the Viljo's oil-cloth factory project failed and was converted to a garment plant.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Armi asked some artist friends to apply their graphic designs to textiles.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] To show how the fabric could be used, the company then designed and sold a line of simple dresses using their fabric.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] When Finland's leading industrial designer Timo Sarpaneva invited the company to present a fashion show (albeit canceled at short notice) at the 1957 Triennale in Milan, it was an early recognition of fashion as an industrial art and of Marimekko's key role in shaping it to that point.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The garments were eventually showcased in the nearby Rinascente upscale department store by display manager Giorgio Armani.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Two pioneering designers set the tone for Marimekko: Vuokko Nurmesniemi in the 1950s and Maija Isola in the 1960s.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Nurmesniemi designed the simply striped red and white *Jokapoika* shirt in 1956.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Isola designed the iconic *Unikko* (poppy) print pattern in 1964.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Marimekko's bold fabrics and bright, simple design strongly influenced late 20th-century taste.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Many of the early Marimekko designs, including Isola's *Unikko*, remain in production in the 2010s.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Marimekko spread to America in the 1960s.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] It was introduced to the United States by the architect Benjamin C.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Thompson, who featured them in his Design Research stores.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] They were made famous in the United States by future first lady Jacqueline Kennedy, who bought eight Marimekko dresses which she wore throughout the 1960 United States presidential campaign.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] By 1965, the company employed over 400 staff, and the company was in every aspect of fine design, from fabrics to toys and dinnerware.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The firm even completely equipped small houses with furnishings.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In 1985, the company was sold to Amer-yhtymä.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In the early 1990s, Marimekko was in a bad financial condition and close to bankruptcy.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] It was bought from Amer by Kirsti Paakkanen, who introduced new business methods in the company and helped to revive its popularity.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Later in the 1990s Marimekko achieved publicity in the hit TV series *Sex and the City*.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The fictional main character of the series, sex-and-relationship columnist Carrie Bradshaw, wore a Marimekko bikini on season 2 and then a Marimekko dress.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In season 5 the series introduced tablecloths with Marimekko prints.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In 2005, Marimekko's revenue had quadrupled since Paakkanen's purchase, and its net income had grown 200-fold.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Paakkanen remained CEO of Marimekko and owned 20% of the company via her business Workidea.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In 2007, Paakkanen announced she would gradually hand over her ownership to Mika Ihamuotila as CEO and biggest owner of the company.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] By 2011 there were 84 stores across the world.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Marimekko products are made in China, India, Thailand, Portugal, Lithuania and other countries.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Fabrics are printed in Marimekko's textile factory in Helsinki, but are not made in Finland.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The company celebrated its 70th anniversary in 2021 by publishing the book *Marimekko: The Art of Printmaking*.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The logo of Marimekko has been in use since 1954.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Armi Ratia wanted the logo to be simple and timeless.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Graphic designer Helge Mether-Borgström used modified versions of classic Olivetti typewriter letters to create the logo.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Cindy Babski wrote in the *New York Times* that "There was never any doubt about what the inside label would say.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] The clothes and fabrics, with their striking design and splashes of bold color, were clearly Marimekko.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In 2007, Heidi Avellan wrote in the Swedish newspaper *Sydsvenskan* that Marimekko was no longer a "statement, just as T-shirts with revolutionary Che Guevara or Palestinian scarves rarely express any political awareness.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Marimekko is paper napkins and rubber boots".
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] She wrote that Marimekko "began with the colourfully striped shirt, *Jokapoika* which Vuokko Nurmesniemi designed in 1956", which became the symbol for new radicalism in academia.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In 2013, allegations were raised accusing Marimekko of plagiarism.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In house designer Kristina Isola later admitted copying design elements from 1963 painting by Ukrainian artist Maria Primachenko.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] By the time the accusations were raised, the design had been painted on the body of one of Finnair's planes, and the National Museum of Ukraniain Folk Art, which held the copyright to Primachenko's design, pursued legal action over the incident.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Finnair moved to repaint the plane as quickly as possible.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] After the incident was raised, other works by Marimekko were identified to be alleged to have strong similarities to works previously released by artists Maria Jauhiainen, Markus Lepo and Heljä Liukko-Sundström.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] Five designs came under suspicion, with Marimekko defending against some claims, and trying to settle others.
[src:marimekko-charts/marimekko] In the case of Lepo's design, Marimekko's CEO later apologised for misleading consumers about the originality of the designs.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] A **mosaic plot**, **Marimekko chart**, **Mekko chart**, or sometimes **percent stacked bar plot**, is a graphical visualization of data from two or more qualitative variables.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] It is the multidimensional extension of spineplots, which graphically display the same information for only one variable.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] It gives an overview of the data and makes it possible to recognize relationships between different variables.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] For example, independence is shown when the boxes across categories all have the same areas.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Mosaic plots were introduced by Hartigan and Kleiner in 1981 and expanded on by Friendly in 1994.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Mosaic plots are also called **Marimekko** or **Mekko charts** because they resemble some Marimekko prints.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] However, in statistical applications, mosaic plots can be colored and shaded according to deviations from independence, whereas Marimekko charts are colored according to the category levels, as in the image.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] As with bar charts and spineplots, the area of the tiles, also known as the bin size, is proportional to the number of observations within that category.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] An example of mosaic plots uses data from the passengers on the *Titanic*.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] There are 2201 observations and 3 variables.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The categorical variables are first put in order.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Then, each variable is assigned to an axis.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] In the table to the right, sequence and classification is presented for this data set.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Another ordering will result in a different mosaic plot, i.e., the order of the variables is significant as for all multivariate plots.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] At the left edge of the first variable we first plot "Gender," meaning that we divide the data vertically in two blocks: the bottom blocks corresponds to females, while the upper (much larger) one to males.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] One immediately sees that roughly a quarter of the passengers were female and the remaining three quarters male.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] One then applies the second variable "Class" to the top edge.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The four vertical columns therefore mark the four values of that variable (1st, 2nd, 3rd, and crew).
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] These columns are of variable thickness, because column width indicates the relative proportion of the corresponding value on the population.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Crew plainly represents the largest male group, whereas third-class passengers are the largest female group.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The number of female crew members is also seen to have been marginal.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The last variable ("Survived") is finally applied, this time along the left edge with the result highlighted by shade: dark grey rectangles represent people that did not survive the disaster, light grey ones people that did.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Women in the first class are immediately seen to have had the highest survival probability.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The survival probability for females is seen to have been higher than that for men (marginalised over all classes).
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Similarly, a marginalization over gender identifies first-class passengers as most probable to survive.
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] Overall, about 1/3 of all people survived (proportion of light gray areas).
[src:marimekko-charts/mosaic-plot] The mosaic plot has been criticised for making the data hard to perceive and to compare visually, because the values correspond to areas.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] A **Pareto chart** is a type of chart that contains both bars and a line graph, where individual values are represented in descending order by bars, and the cumulative total is represented by the line.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The chart is named for the Pareto principle, which, in turn, derives its name from Vilfredo Pareto, a noted Italian economist.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] Its purpose is to assess the most frequently occurring defects by category.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The left vertical axis is the frequency of occurrence, but it can alternatively represent cost or another important unit of measure.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The right vertical axis is the cumulative percentage of the total number of occurrences, total cost, or total of the particular unit of measure.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] Because the values are in decreasing order, the cumulative function is a concave function.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] To take the example below, in order to lower the amount of late arrivals by 78%, it is sufficient to solve the first three issues.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The Pareto Chart demonstrates a power law relationship between the rank of a quality issue and that issue's contribution to cost.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] This means one can find a linear relationship on a log-log plot.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The purpose of the Pareto chart is to highlight the most important among a (typically large) set of factors.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] In quality control, Pareto charts are useful to find the defects to prioritize in order to observe the greatest overall improvement.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] It often represents the most common sources of defects, the highest occurring type of defect, or the most frequent reasons for customer complaints, and so on.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] Wilkinson (2006) devised an algorithm for producing statistically based acceptance limits (similar to confidence intervals) for each bar in the Pareto chart.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] These charts can be generated by simple spreadsheet programs, specialized statistical software tools, and online quality charts generators.
[src:marimekko-charts/pareto-chart] The Pareto chart is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:marimekko-charts/stacked-bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:marimekko-charts/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
